segments.text: You can be general.
I'm going to give a name because I'm proud of this young man.
We had a player named Lester Hayes.
Oh, of course.
And you probably remember Lester Hayes.
Yes, I do.
One of the things that was unique about him was he was a defensive back, and he discovered that the more stick them he put on his hands, the more balls he intercepted.
And by the time he got into the pros, he would actually have grease all over his hands, and they finally patched the Lester Hayes rule that prevented that.
But Lester had a speech impediment.
You remember that, I'm sure.
And a basketball player named Randy Knowles, who was a real good shooter, was in my class.
And I'm blocking the tackle right now.
There was a defensive tackle in that class, a big guy.
He was also black.
Of course, Randy Knowles was a white guy, and Lester was black, and so was this fella.
And they were a lot of fun.
They kept the class moving, but I could tell they often were not prepared for class.
And I worried about Lester, whether or not he was going to be able to survive in this environment or not, until after class one day, he and this defensive tackle
were having a discussion.
And it was an informal discussion about defensive football.
And Lester outlined one of the most succinct explanations of defensive system I'd ever seen.
And he stumbled and stuttered and did it, but it was really intricate.
And I thought, this guy is not a dumb guy.
He might have some disadvantages, but he's not dumb.
Later on, as he was drafted in the pros, he was, after one of his really good games, they interviewed him on TV.
I saw the interview, in fact.
And, of course, he was excited.
He had won the game, and he was nervous, and he could not make a sentence.
He didn't get three words together.
He saw that in a rerun and was so embarrassed by it until he went to school then and got some help and learned to combat that speech impediment.
And the last time I heard him, he was
Very controlled kind of conversation.
I don't know when I've ever been more proud of a young man.
All right, now, I'm trying, my brain is trying to recall, there was somebody else, some other athlete's wife, who was trained in speech therapy.
I think maybe you're right.
Who helped him some.
Yeah.
I think maybe you're right about that.
I didn't know where he went for his help.
Because there was a at one point there was a worry as to whether Lester could pass everything here and his lack of confidence and so forth.
Did anybody ever twist your arm about a grade for an athlete?
Never did.
I don't think I ever recall any.
But I made
I made it clear very early on.
I had been a coach, and I knew what coaches did.
And I made it very clear that I was going to do two things, that they were going to be treated fairly in my class.
When I was in college, I can remember going to a chemistry class one morning.
And this happened pretty often.
And the instructor said, how many basketball players are here?
And you raise your hand, and he'd say, you might as well drop this class.
You cannot make it in here.
You're going to miss some classes, and you can't make it.
And it got to the point where you were afraid to answer that question.
Because other classes, they'd say, how many basketball players are here?
And you raise your hand, I like basketball.
I'm glad you're here.
And you got to where you were gun shy about whether to raise your hand or not raise your hand.
And so one of the first things I'd tell my athletes was, you're going to be treated fairly in this class.
And I know you represent the university.
You're going to miss some classes.
And you'll be allowed to make up everything that can be made up.
But I'm not going to keep you eligible.
You're going to have to do that on your own.
And I did that early on.
And so I never had a lot of problems.
But the one time I think I was going to be approached was when Coach Sherrill was here.
I was department head then.
And he called me over to Kane Hall for lunch.
And I'm not sure yet what the purpose of that meeting was.
It might have been just to get to know them.
Because we have always had a good relationship with athletics, unlike a lot of schools where health and physical education athletics were at war with one another.
We never had that kind of relationship here.
But Coach Cheryl had me over to lunch at Kane Hall.

and we visited and talked and a lot of people came by the table and when we got through I could tell he was about to say something and before he opened his mouth I said coach I want to tell you how much we how pleased we are that you're here and I want to tell you that we've always had a real good relationship with between our two departments and and I sure hope we can can maintain that but but there's there's a couple things you need to know number one
And I went through the same spiel about how we treated athletes in our department.
And I said, you can count on that.
If they have to miss, we'll help them make it up.
We're not going to keep them eligible.
And the second thing is, I won't be a dumping ground for your worn-out coaches.
If you don't want them, I don't want them.
And he kind of cleared his throat and said, there's no shortcuts in this business.
And that's the only comment that he made.
And consequently, we got along very well.
But I have to say, I never was approached.
Were you ever approached as a faculty member?
No, no, I never was.
I never was.
Occasionally, and I knew a good many coaches personally, occasionally a coach would see me in the hallway and say, hey, how's so-and-so doing?
But I never had any arm twisted or anything.
I never did.
When Ballard was here, I was one of the people that he called on when it was still legal to do so.
When he'd have athletes here for the weekend, I'd go over on Saturdays and talk to them about the institution actually and so forth.
I remember talking to Bubba Bean.
Describe the relationship
between the Department of Athletics and the Department of, and did the name change of your department in the 70s or early 80s?
Yeah, it changed in the 80s, somewhere around 83, 84.
And what was the name change?
It was changed from health and physical education to health and kinesiology.
And it actually really reflects what's going on in what was then physical education better.
We made the change ourselves, but it was not without motivation.
We had wanted to change it for some time.
In fact, the field, the discipline felt the need to change.
But there wasn't
We couldn't get an agreement as to what we wanted to be.
We couldn't even get an agreement within our own department.
But what happened was that there was a guy from Delmont, and I'm forgetting his name.
I thought I never would forget it.
He was chairman of education for the legislature, chairman of the education committee.
And he got the legislature to pass a law.
And you may have been at UTEP at that time.
I can't remember exactly.
But the law was that you could have no more than six hours of education in your curriculum.
And that put
And the way they interpreted that law was that any word, anytime you had the word education, that meant that was an education course.
So music education was an education course.
Health education was an education course.
Physical education was an education course.
So we were forced to change.
And of course we made the case that not all of our courses were education.
Some of them were discipline specific, others were methodology, and those were education.
So it was easy to get consensus because we knew that our future depended on it.
But in making that change, it better reflects what's going on in physical education.
The old physical education programs is only a very small part of what is done over there now.
Exercise physiology, motor learning, biomechanics, those are the big things now.
And I regret that some.
But the relationship of our department to athletics has always been a very good one.
Carl Landis, I think he did, he started that.
I don't know if he started it or not, but he certainly kept it going.
Of course, Walter Penberthy came here as intramural director, and he was hired by the Department of Athletics to run the intramural program and later to become department head.
So there was always that relationship.
And if you go back far enough, most of the coaches were faculty members in physical education.
So when Carl came along, he did nothing to hurt that.
In fact, enhanced it.
And I hope I did the same thing.
There were a lot of good that came out of that.
Number one, we weren't throwing rocks at each other and constantly doing damage to people that didn't deserve it.
Secondly, we got some nice things out of it.
For example, they wanted, Emory Ballard wanted to expand the football stadium.
But if you build that football stadium, you have to have something to hold it up.
And he didn't quite have enough money to, you know this story better than I do, he didn't have enough money to build the stadium, so they wanted to tap the permanent university fund.
But you couldn't use a permanent university fund for athletics.
So, hence, we got a brand new building, a health and physical education, a much needed building, I might add, and doubled our square footage.
Describe those facilities.
Oh, at the time, they were state of the art.
We've kind of been passed now, but...

There was new administrative offices on the first floor, which were superb, complete with conference rooms and faculty offices, classrooms, which have been recently upgraded, by the way, in their state of the art.
Now the classrooms are.
On the second floor were our labs, human performance labs, dance studios, and those kinds of things.
Fourth floor was gymnasiums, and the last floor was gymnasium.
We went from a
from a situation where everybody was doubled up and sometimes tripled up in offices so that we all had private offices.
And we never would have gotten that.
Well, it would have been very difficult to have gotten that, apart from athletics.
They were the point people on that.
Then Jackie Sherrill came along and wanted a state-of-the-art weight room, a conditioning room.
And so he built the STEED.
What does he call that?
Strength and Conditioning Laboratory.
which is really an exercise room.
But once again, he didn't have quite enough money to build the whole building.
So he agreed that a third of the building could belong to our department.
And in return, they got to use some permanent university money for that.
And we built the human performance laboratory over there, which is, I'm probably sitting in this chair because that lab is over there.
Because one of the things they do over there is stress testing with physician supervision and monitoring the heart at the same time.
And that's how they found my heart condition.
I didn't know I was even a problem.
And consequently, they caught it, corrected it, or at least treated it.
And I was a walking time bomb.
I was 90% occluded and didn't know it.
So some nice things have occurred as a result of that relationship.
Now we've taken some hits because of it, too.
Being that closely related, there are a lot in the academic community who will equate us with them.
And it's been a constant battle to remind everyone that we're an academic program.
And sometimes it's hurt us.
On the whole, I wouldn't, you know, the good has been better than the bad, I think.
I'm not going to ask the negative.
Of all the coaches and athletic department personnel you all have worked with, to which ones would you give the highest grades?
Who was the most positive and helpful?
Oh, Wally Groff is outstanding.
He really is good.
I understand that former students are burning him a little bit now, and primarily it's because of him.
the one loss records, overall one loss records.
But anyone who knows Wiley knows he's first class.
We didn't really have a bad situation.
Of course, I didn't go back as far as Barry Bryant, so I don't know that story.
But I don't recall a bad situation, even when Coach Sherrill was here.
And, of course, he pushed the edge of the envelope a lot of the time.
I still had no relationship problem with him.
But Wally is by far the best we've had.
In the late 70s and 80s, what were some of the stepping stones that caused you and your colleagues to know that things were moving forward?
Well, I took the liberty of writing down some things, mainly because you warned me that you might ask me that question.
I think in the time I was here, the College of Education had just been created about two years before my arrival.
It had come out of science, and they lumped ADCI and Ag Ed and us and some others together.
And that was an important move, I think, for allowing us to develop the way we should have.

But in 1973, we got our undergraduate curriculum in health education approved, which allowed us to have those individuals who wanted to go into school health could major in health education, and those who wanted to work in
in public health and places like that could major in community health.
So it did two things.
It opened up the health curriculum, but it also, for the first time, made it possible to, in our department, to get a degree without being teacher certified.
You could do something a little different.
In 1974, we developed a cardiac rehab program.

Dr. George Jessup was the person who primarily did that along with Baylor College of Medicine and we began to develop majors who could actually work in cardiac rehab facilities and we helped with the development of the Methodist Hospitals program in cardiac rehab.
Prior to that,
the allied health program that we've talked about before in here that we have.
It was a consortium between us and Baylor College of Medicine and the University of Houston.
And to some degree, that relationship that was established with Baylor and us helped, I think, with the relationship that later was established for the med school.
But I wouldn't
I can't take much credit for that, but the discussion that went on at the upper administration level opened that door, I think.

Then Carl Landis had already established a lot of our laboratories, but in moving to our new building, we were able to build the mechanical analysis lab, the human performance lab, the motor performance lab.
And for the first time we were doing research that was legitimate research that could hold us on with any in the, not any in the university, but most in the university.
Then in the fall of 74, it was kind of a benchmark happening for the activity program.
There was an attack on the program.
There were some on campus that wanted to do away with that program, and there always was some.
But as a result of that attack, the program actually got strengthened.
For the first time, at least since I've been here, they began to give college credit for those courses.
Prior to that time, you'll recall, it was possible to have better than a four-point average
because you got those added on.
This changed the way they operated there.
And I think it gave us a little more respect for the program.
Then a major thing happened was with the Project 2000.
Is that what they called that then?
The Board of Regents Initiative, Project 2000, changed
our perspective made us look at graduate programs a lot more than we had before.
And that affected everybody in the university and certainly affected us.
In 1973, they also added an expansion to G. Raleigh White.
And for the first time, there was women's locker rooms.
There had never been women's locker rooms prior to that.
They were dressed in a little closet area.
And women's bathrooms.
And there were some other facilities added.
And that changed the complexion of the university.
And about that time was when we began to see a lot more women show up on campus.
And I can remember walking down the hall in G. Raleigh one morning going to class, and two guys were in front of me.
And one of them said to the other one that said, you know, when I came here, I didn't see one pretty girl in a month.
Now I see one everywhere I look.
And the first time I thought of it, the scenery was changing considerably on campus.
Then in 1980, we opened what was then called East Cal.
It later became known as the Reed Building, which is the building we're in now.
And that was a biggie.
That really made a difference.
Carl Landis did most of the
of the work on that building.
I got the credit for it because it opened under my administration, but he really did the work there.
In 1980, we were introduced to a guy named Tom Reed, and that was a really big thing for the department, I think.
Is it okay to talk a little bit about that?
Oh, please do.
And tell us about his background.
That story is, I think, kind of an unusual one.
Tom Reed grew up in Lakeland or Lakeview, and I'm sorry I don't know the Ohio.
It's an outskirt of Cleveland.
He grew up during the 40s and so he was drafted into or joined the Army Air Force.
And he flew transport airplanes.
He flew the Burma Hump.
That was one of his major assignments.
And upon getting out of the service,
He took the GI Bill and went to college.
He went to a school called Kinney College, Kinney College in Ohio.
Small liberal arts school.
Paul Newman was in that school.
And Jonathan, Jonathan who, the comedian, Jonathan.
Waters?
No.
No, no, no.
Winters, Winters.
Winters.
Jonathan Winters, yeah.
They were both in his class.
And it wasn't about 500 students in the whole school, I think.
Well, while he was in school there, he opened the first bookstore they'd ever had in that school, you know, where they sold peanuts and popcorns and paper and that kind of thing.
He said he made so much money until he decided he needed college, so he dropped out of school.
Dropped out and almost immediately the store went belly up.
But he never did finish school.
He kind of diddled back and forth.
And so while looking for a job, a friend of his was working for a guy named Fred Lennon, who manufactured pipe fittings and talked Tom into working for him.
Now, that itself is kind of a unique story.
All this fished together down the road a piece.
Fred Lennon was...
was a marketing person.
That was his specialty.
And there was another man named Crawford who was an engineer.
Crawford manufactured or invented this pipe fitting, a unique way of fitting pipes together.
It's called Swaglock is the brand name now.
And he wanted to market it, but he didn't know how, so he partnered with Fred Lennon, and they marketed it and did pretty well.
Well, Lennon, being a businessman, wanted to go into Cleveland, build a foundry, and actually do this big time, which would incur a lot of debt.
And Crawford, being an academician, didn't want to do that, so he sold out to Lennon for something under $20,000, according to Tom Reed.
Well, Lennon went into Cleveland, built his foundry, and the short of it is he's now the largest
manufacturer of pipe fittings in the entire world, worth billions of dollars.
Tom went to work for him and they sent him to Houston.
He said he was just a peddler.
He said, I had my inventory in the trunk of the car and kept my books in the front seat.
My territory was Texas, Oklahoma, New Mexico, Arkansas, Louisiana.
He had a huge territory.
which he quickly narrowed down.
And he became very successful.
A couple of things happened to him.
One, he developed a unique way of marketing in that he identified vice presidents.
He called them vice presidents.
And he set each of those people up in a warehouse.
And he liked athletes an awful lot because he liked the competitiveness of their nature.
And he had five of those guys eventually.
Each one of them had their own store.
And he took a piece of the action out of each store.
But the understanding was that when he retired, he would give them their store.
He would set them up in business, in effect.
They just had to wait for deferred gratification.
And that was successful.
But being in the pipe business, he also was close to the oil business.
And so he got in on the bottom floor of the Midland Odessa oil field and invested in a few of those wells and never had a dry hole.
He had five or six wells that came in.
And consequently, he became very wealthy.
Now here's where the story begins to tie together.
He said that when he was a youngster, he played baseball.
And in the summertime, he'd look around and all of his friends would be gone.
And he discovered that they were off in summer camp.
His parents, though, weren't poor, but they didn't feel like it was in the middle of the Depression or end of the Depression.
He didn't feel like that they could send him to camp.
So he made himself a promise that when he got rich, he was going to build a camp for kids who couldn't go to camp, like we all play those kind of games.
Well, when he became very successful, he remembered that promise, and he wanted to do something good, and so he decided to build a camp.
And he went out to San Diego out in the desert area, bought some property, was going to build his camp out there.
For some reason he discovered that he didn't, that was not a good deal.
One thing is he liked to be a hands-on type person and Houston was a long way from San Diego.
So he decided not to build a camp, but he held the property for a while and sold it and made an obscene profit off of it because San Diego was moving out in that direction.
So then he bought some property in Kerrville and decided that he would build a camp there.
And he actually started construction.
But he went over there one day, and his builder, who was a sheriff of the county, had more of his building materials on the sheriff's home than he did out in the property.
So he got discouraged and said, well, maybe the good Lord just doesn't want me to build this camp.
But he held on the land a while and sold it.
And he said again, the profit was so great.
He said it was tremendous what he made off that profit.
And he said, well, maybe the Lord does want me to do this.
So finally he found this place down in Magnolia.
And it was about 35 acres.
It had a small cabin on it.
And that's where he began to clear off the land and build some cabins.
And the first I knew anything about it, Bob Rutledge, do you recall him, called me one day and said, I was department head, and said, Len,
how would you like to have $100,000 in scholarships?
I said, well, I'd like to have $100,000 in scholarships.
I said, well, I got a guy down in Houston that's going to give you some.
I said, but he wants to talk to you.
He's going to give you the money no matter what, but I want you to go down and listen to him.
And so I discovered that what he was looking for was someone to run the camp for him.
He'd had some bad experiences.
He first tried to get a
an employee to run it, and that just didn't work out very well for him.
So I went down there expecting to see some pup tents by a creek.
And what I saw was about a million dollar plant.
It was really, really well underway then.
And it didn't take long to figure out that'd be a good thing for us to get involved in.
And so we took one of our lecturers who taught in the activity program who didn't have summer employment and made him the director.
We took some of our majors and made them the counselors.
And we went down to run the camp.
And it happened that this fellow, his name was Bob Pankey, was the lecturer that I'd chosen.
P-A-N-K-E-Y.
And he had worked in I think a Bob White.
What's Bob White's dad's name that worked here?
You're talking about Camp... Camp Kanekut.
Kanekut, up in Missouri.
Right, and I can't think of his dad's name now, but you know who I'm talking about.
I want to say Jojo, and that's not quite right.
Yeah, Jojo's his son, and Joe and Bob, and his dad's name is... We'll think of it later.
Of course, the Penberths were close to them.
Well, Bob Pankey had worked at Camp Kanekut and knew a little bit about that, and so he developed his program, and
And I would go down two or three times and look at it.
And at the end of the summer, Tom called me in and said, this is the best I've ever had this camp run.
I want to keep this going.
And here's another check for $100,000.
And so we were encouraged by that.
and found out that the counselors were really getting good experiences because they were working with youngsters that they were going to be working with.
So we went back the next year and ran the camp again.
At the end of that year, he gave us a check for $250,000.
And so he's been very generous with us along the way.
And then not a few years ago, about eight or ten years ago, his health started deteriorating.
And being a person that wanted hands-on type operation, he wanted someone down at the camp
And he asked me one day if I thought that if he gave a chair to the university, would that lock us into that camp?
And of course, we assured him that it would.
And so he gave us a $500,000 matched chair.
And then later, I was named to that chair, which was undeservedly so.
But nevertheless, it worked out good.
And that's about the time I decided to step down as department head.
So in the summer, I worked down there.
I'm back and forth between there and the university.
And his name?
His name is Tom Reed, R-E-A-D.
What's good about that was he continued to give us discretionary money in the denominator, about $25,000 a year.
And he's done that for, or did that until his death, and his widow has continued now, and it's been about 10 or 15 years that he's done that kind of thing.
That's been a big deal for us.
And consequently, we named our building the Reed Building because of that.
He died about nine years ago.
And his widow has continued to be very generous with him.
I think that relationship was an important one because we have been able to do some things that we wouldn't have been able to do without those funds.
Prior to that, the Omar Smith chair had come our way.
And that also was a big thing.
You remember Omar was a tennis coach here.
And Bob Walker helped us get that chair.
It was given to us as stock in the Deer Queens.
and wasn't funded until about five or six years ago.
But that was a benchmark for us.
Then we developed an outdoor education institute.
Mickey Little did that while she was here.
And another benchmark was the emergency medical care program that Laura Kitzmiller put together.
Laura was really the main person and the only person that ran that program for a good long time.
And that's been a major, major benchmark.
The other important thing we did along the way was the recruiting of minorities.
Just in a quick and dirty way, those are the highlights that I would
I would put together.
How did you recruit those minorities?
Well, we finally decided that they weren't going to come to us.
We just had to go find them.
And so we called some people that we knew that had minorities in their undergraduate programs.
What kind of folks?
Well, at Northwestern was our colleagues over there in health and physical education.
We knew that they had Northwest Louisiana.
And there was a guy named Frank Ashley who
They had recently graduated, and he had gone to Alabama for his doctorate and was finishing.
And so we were able to look him up and bring him on.
And of course, Frank is now the director of admissions at A&M.
And he really helped us bring others in when you just get that first one.
We had another kid named Butler that came in as a lecturer and then got his doctorate while he was here.
But we still aren't very good at it.
We have a good mix of men and women, but a minority is still, it's a hard fight.
Let's go back.
Carl Landis served as department head until when?
Until 1979.
And I don't remember what year he started.
Did you succeed him?
I succeeded him.
Describe how that came about.
What was the process and how were you identified and so forth?
I don't know that I was ready for that job, and I'm sure they weren't thinking about me.
Linus Dow was the heir apparent.
